        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Down Farnborough | Kent</placeName>
                    <date>Oct 14<hi rend="superscript">th</hi></date>
                    <salute>Dear Madam</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I am extremely much obliged by your kindness in sending me so capital a suite of male &amp; female specimens. I am surprised at their not being a marked difference in the size of their wings:<ref target="#foot.f1"/> what you tell me of the wings of the female being smaller than those of the male, in their early growth is quite new to me.<ref target="#foot.f2"/> I hope to get a friend to enquire how these facts are with the species in India.<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p>
<p>I am sincerely grateful for your kind promise to make further observations, on the points which interest me next summer.</p>
<p>Pray believe me, dear Madam | Yours truly obliged | C. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-1113.xml" resp="#automat">letter to M. A. T. Whitby, 2 September [1847]</ref>, for CD’s interest in variation in the moths raised from silkworms.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Cited in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_7951.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Variation</hi></ref> 1: 303. Mrs Whitby’s letter has not been found.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-1174.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to J. D. Hooker, 10 May 1848</ref>.</note>
